WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.220 --> 00:00:03.320
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: All right. Thanks for
coming today. My name is Brian Fitzpatrick,

00:00:03.320 --> 00:00:08.700
here at Google Chicago. And I'm very happy
to have our guest here, who is no stranger

00:00:08.700 --> 00:00:09.700
to this office.

00:00:09.700 --> 00:00:10.700
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: That's true.

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:11.700
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick : Dan Sinker.

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:14.420
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I'm sorry. I'm drinking my water
just as he said my name.

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:18.189
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick : Oh that's, by all means.
If you can talk while you're, tweet while

00:00:18.189 --> 00:00:19.800
anonymously, if you can talk while you're
drinking.

00:00:19.800 --> 00:00:20.800
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: It's true.

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:26.349
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick : But Dan Sinker, as many
people know him, at MayorEmanuel. So, thanks

00:00:26.349 --> 00:00:27.349
for coming today, Dan.

00:00:27.349 --> 00:00:28.509
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Thanks for having me. This is
awesome.

00:00:28.509 --> 00:00:31.731
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick : It's great to have you
back. So, a little bit of the history. I mean,

00:00:31.731 --> 00:00:33.750
you've been here before. What do you usually
come here for?

00:00:33.750 --> 00:00:38.000
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I have. Usually I come here.
I convince Fitz to allow me to bring students

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.740
here. I teach at Columbia College Chicago
in the Journalism Department and I teach kind

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:50.570
of various formats of digital journalism.
And a big part of what I do is teach teach

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:52.230
kids how to build stuff on the web.

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:56.920
And Fitz has been very, very thoughtful enough
to allow my classes to come here and actually

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:01.950
present their final projects to some of you
guys. I recognize some faces here, and to

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:07.470
other folks that we invite in. So, yeah. I'm
definitely no stranger to these offices, which

00:01:07.470 --> 00:01:11.070
made writing about Rahm's visit to Google
much more fun.

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:13.030
[audience laughs]
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick : Well, I think maybe

00:01:13.030 --> 00:01:14.510
we should just start right into that.

00:01:14.510 --> 00:01:15.880
[Dan Sinker laughs]

00:01:15.880 --> 00:01:19.560
So, it sounds like at MayorEmanuel had a heck
of a trip when he came here.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:24.890
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. Well, I mean that was
the thing, right? The funny thing about writing

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:29.881
a fictional story about a guy running for
mayor in a city where you know a lot of people,

00:01:29.881 --> 00:01:35.659
right? And and is he kept visiting places
that I was friends with people there.

00:01:35.659 --> 00:01:44.940
So it allowed me to kind of make merciless
fun of those places, knowing that there would

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:49.010
be people that would appreciate it. So, yeah,
when he came to Google, he spent he spent,

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:58.439
the whole morning topping up on nerdery. So,
his intern, Carl, who over the course of the

00:01:58.439 --> 00:02:03.690
story kept getting more and more. Two things
happened with Carl as the story progressed.

00:02:03.690 --> 00:02:05.460
He kept getting younger.

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:12.370
Like, he started as a twentyish year old college
intern and by the end of it he was a high

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:20.450
school kid, 16 years old. And he also kept
getting more and more geeky, right, till literally

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:27.160
the last day. They pick him up after Mathletes
practice at Lane Tech. And so, Carl was beside

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:31.550
himself with excitement that he was gonna
be speaking at Google. So he had to memorize

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:34.170
Pi down to a certain number of digits.

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:37.380
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Not an interview question.
Just to be clear.

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:38.459
[Dan Sinker laughs]

00:02:38.459 --> 00:02:45.350
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: And David Axlerod was getting
him to memorize Monty Python lines and he

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:49.940
had been up all night getting a D and D character
together just in case. I believe the quote

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:54.810
was, "just in case anyone throws down a twentyside."
[audience laughs]

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:59.830
But yeah. But then he shows up and I actually
don't know anything about his appearance here.

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:00.982
Neither do you. You totally weren't here.

00:03:00.982 --> 00:03:01.982
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I was in Australia.

00:03:01.982 --> 00:03:02.982
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I know.

00:03:02.982 --> 00:03:03.982
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Yeah.

00:03:03.982 --> 00:03:06.600
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I was like, "Oh my God. I'm
gonna write about Google 'cause Fitz is there."

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:08.390
And then you're off on a cruise.

00:03:08.390 --> 00:03:13.240
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: No, I was in New Zealand
at Foo Camp down there and furiously logging

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:14.950
in as people are telling me that--

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:15.950
[Dan Sinker laughs]

00:03:15.950 --> 00:03:18.920
Mayor Emanuel was at your office being chased
by people on segways.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:26.921
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: By Eric Schmidt on a Segway
was mine. And yeah, they end up Segway jousting

00:03:26.921 --> 00:03:34.640
out on Kinsey [audience chuckles] and then
being chased. I believe the setup is that

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:40.930
Schmidt totally knocks him on his ass in Segway
jousting, which has anyone actually ever Segway

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:42.201
jousted? It seems fun in my head.

00:03:42.201 --> 00:03:43.819
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I've seen Segway juggling,
but.

00:03:43.819 --> 00:03:48.340
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah, I think Segway jousting.
'Cause it would be, they're hard to knock

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:50.870
over. So you've really got to work at that
thing, right?

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:52.800
[audience chuckles]

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:57.770
But anyway, he knocks him on his ass and then
starts giving a speech.[Brian Fitzpatrick

00:03:57.770 --> 00:04:04.120
laughs] And Axlerod recognizes this speech
is coming out of the film, "Three Hundred."

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:12.550
And so he just tells Rahm, "OK, when he gets
to the line, like madness, this is Google,

00:04:12.550 --> 00:04:14.849
we just need to start running."

00:04:14.849 --> 00:04:21.780
And so, they end up taking off running and
the line in the story is, "And now we're being

00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:29.520
chased by 300 nerds." Or, "three hundred geeks
on Segways. Geeks with motherfucking swords."

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:30.730
Or something to that effect.

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:31.730
[Brian Fitzpatrick laughs]

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:36.350
And they end up hiding under the LaSalle Bridge
until everyone realizes that they're missing

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:40.830
Stargate SG-One. And they go wheeling off
on their Segways. So.

00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:44.550
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So you're saying you
wanna ride on my Segway? Is that what you're

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:45.550
saying here?

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:48.169
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I've ridden on your Segway.
That thing is terrifying, man.

00:04:48.169 --> 00:04:49.169
[laughter]

00:04:49.169 --> 00:04:53.660
That is all power to people that can handle
that. But I thought I was gonna die for the

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:56.810
two minutes that I like, moved at one mile
an hour.

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:57.860
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Four feet?

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:00.081
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Rocking back and forth like
this the whole way.

00:05:00.081 --> 00:05:06.800
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: You've got "Three Hundred
" in here. We've got "Stargate SG-One." We've

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:11.750
got fermented baby food that causes people
to hallucinate. Were you under the influence

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:13.430
of any illicit drugs while you were writing
this?

00:05:13.430 --> 00:05:18.590
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I wasn't. People keep saying
that. But especially my students. And

00:05:18.590 --> 00:05:20.250
[laughter]

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:27.590
I wasn't at all. It's just really fun to write
hallucination, right? And it's fun to write

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:36.509
things that start at one point and then end
really, really far off of that point and the

00:05:36.509 --> 00:05:37.570
more sideways you can get.

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:45.080
And definitely, as the story line progressed,
like the more kind of like geek references

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:50.340
and the comic book references and sci-fi references
and stuff like that that you can really subtlety

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:58.490
work in, the better. Down to the second to
last tweet has just this perfect, awesome

00:05:58.490 --> 00:06:03.960
"Empire Strikes Back" subtle reference in
there that almost nobody picked up on. But

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:09.040
the other thing about Carl the Intern was
he was this awesome, gay teenager and he was

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:13.419
secretly in love with Rahm Emanuel. And at
the end of it, he

00:06:13.419 --> 00:06:14.889
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: A Monty Burns sort of
thing.

00:06:14.889 --> 00:06:22.610
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah, yeah. I guess so. But
at the very end, second to last tweet, as

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:30.930
Mayor Emanuel is disintegrating into time,
itself, Carl just says, "I love you." And

00:06:30.930 --> 00:06:32.300
Mayor Emanuel responds, "I know."

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:33.500
[laughter]

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:39.650
Such a great little "Empire" moment in there.
And it went over a lot of people's heads.

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:41.620
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Well, it's admittedly
subtle.

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:42.620
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: It is, yeah.

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:43.620
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: But--.

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:48.110
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: There was a much less subtle
"Empire" reference where an entire morning

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:54.300
with Bill Clinton was reliving the whole Hoth
Wampa scene in "Empire."

00:06:54.300 --> 00:06:57.411
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Right. Right. Right.
Well actually, let's back up for a second.

00:06:57.411 --> 00:06:58.950
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. Let's back up for a second.

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:02.960
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: We've got two amazing
fantasy sequences where you can basically

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:04.100
do whatever you want, right?

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:05.100
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:08.130
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I mean, that's like,
talking about the Simpson's. Simpson's writers

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:11.740
have said that one of the reasons that they
loved Monty Burns so much,might even have

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:14.853
been Harry Shearer, I don't know who it was,but
is that it gives you the freedom to do anything.

00:07:14.853 --> 00:07:15.880
The sky has unlimited wealth.

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:16.880
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:20.530
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So, how did you get there?
When you first started off, I mean, the first

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:23.699
very few tweets, it was just like a whole
lot of profanity, right?

00:07:23.699 --> 00:07:30.860
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes. Definitely. I mean, the
thing started not even really knowing it was

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:35.800
a thing. I mean, I think that's the way a
lot of people start projects is you don't

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:39.620
really know you've started that project until
you're well into that project.

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:45.100
And so, that was certainly true with this.
It started late at night. Like, looking at

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:49.770
the timestamps on the tweets, it was like
post 10:30, which meant my kid was in bed

00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:53.600
and my wife had probably gone to bed early
that night as well. So I'm just hanging out

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:59.290
on the couch. And this was the end of September,
so there were a lot of.

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:05.229
P had just gone live with a story that Rahm
Emanuel was gonna leave the White House. There

00:08:05.229 --> 00:08:10.889
had already been a lot of rumors that he was
gonna run for mayor, but this was the first

00:08:10.889 --> 00:08:15.069
understanding that he was actually gonna leave
the White House. This was before the midterms.

00:08:15.069 --> 00:08:17.039
Quite early in terms of when people thought.

00:08:17.039 --> 00:08:24.259
P went live. The Tribune went live. It suddenly
became a big story and I have no idea why

00:08:24.259 --> 00:08:28.880
that night it's sitting there by myself. It
just seemed like, "Well, that would be a funny

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:36.050
thing to do, wouldn't it?" And so, it started.
And yeah, I mean the early first few weeks

00:08:36.050 --> 00:08:42.629
of the account, it was just, it was raw. The
profanity is pretty insane.

00:08:42.629 --> 00:08:45.210
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I'd hate to break it
to you, but it's pretty insane the whole way

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:46.210
through.

00:08:46.210 --> 00:08:52.209
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Well, except that it got a lot
more utilitarian, right? Early on, a lot of

00:08:52.209 --> 00:08:59.360
what was entertaining to me was like, "What
word can I add to a hyphenated profanity to

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:08.160
make it just disgusting?" So, it was just
really gross. Like, reading it now it's like,

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:09.160
"That's really gross."

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:12.790
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: At last count, there
were over two hundred of these hyphenated--.

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:17.230
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes, there were. There were.
But that stuff dropped off especially as the

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:22.300
story-telling increased. Oftentimes, a tweet
would get written where you'd write the tweet

00:09:22.300 --> 00:09:27.480
and then be like, "Oh, wait. I've gotta fold
a 'motherfucker' in here." Or something like

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:28.480
that.

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:29.480
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: People called you out
on that a few times, right?

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:33.019
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes, every time. The best part
was that every time you would send one off

00:09:33.019 --> 00:09:38.509
without, you would immediately hear. And that
person thought that they had just discovered

00:09:38.509 --> 00:09:43.029
a leprechaun. Like, that person would be like,
"This is the first tweet ever without any

00:09:43.029 --> 00:09:44.029
swearing."

00:09:44.029 --> 00:09:48.170
And it's like, "No, look. Two weeks ago there
was one, too." And that guy also thought he'd

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:49.389
found the only one ever.

00:09:49.389 --> 00:09:52.490
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Yeah. And you follow
it up with a tweet of nothing but swear.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:57.579
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah, yeah. Usually you would
then overcompensate for a while. But yeah.

00:09:57.579 --> 00:10:02.459
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Well, so it's interesting.
That brings up the point of people were replying

00:10:02.459 --> 00:10:05.920
to you in real time. So, there's a couple
of issues here. One, the story's unfolding

00:10:05.920 --> 00:10:10.111
and it seems like a pretty obvious thing for
at Mayor Emanuel to be angry about because

00:10:10.111 --> 00:10:12.769
why does he have to go through this with this
election?

00:10:12.769 --> 00:10:13.769
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

00:10:13.769 --> 00:10:16.550
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I mean, there's. He clearly
believes there's just no contest here and

00:10:16.550 --> 00:10:17.550
I'm wasting my time.

00:10:17.550 --> 00:10:24.519
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Right. That's the conceit. The
whole early part of the story is this guy

00:10:24.519 --> 00:10:31.019
basically being like, "Oh my God. I have to
do this, too?" Like he knows he's gonna be

00:10:31.019 --> 00:10:39.959
elected but still has to perform all the duties
that you have to do when you're elected. And

00:10:39.959 --> 00:10:45.290
every single one of them is irksome to him.
I mean, that's totally the character.

00:10:45.290 --> 00:10:50.619
The actual person seemed to love that stuff.
I mean, God, he went to an el Stop every day,

00:10:50.619 --> 00:10:54.470
right? Whereas my character, each el Stop
he just got more and more annoyed with the

00:10:54.470 --> 00:11:00.869
whole thing. I think by the end of like, the
first week, he's like, "Whoever runs janitorial

00:11:00.869 --> 00:11:03.199
for the CTA, I wanna take a meeting with that
guy."

00:11:03.199 --> 00:11:06.119
[laughter]

00:11:06.119 --> 00:11:12.069
But yeah. He's just really annoyed with the
process of running for mayor. It all just

00:11:12.069 --> 00:11:13.700
seems like a big pain in his ass.

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:16.910
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So then, people start
replying to you.

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:17.910
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:20.589
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: And the story's unfolding
in real time as the election is going on.

00:11:20.589 --> 00:11:24.949
But how did that affect things? You had all
these people talking to you while you're story.

00:11:24.949 --> 00:11:26.879
You're getting instant feedback. Tell me more
about that.

00:11:26.879 --> 00:11:33.309
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: So this is the thing that I
actually think is really interesting. And

00:11:33.309 --> 00:11:39.740
it's something I've thought about a lot and
now that the story's done and out and a lot

00:11:39.740 --> 00:11:42.019
of other people are starting to dissect it
as well.

00:11:42.019 --> 00:11:48.790
But you had people that have written fiction
on Twitter before. But typically what they

00:11:48.790 --> 00:11:54.149
do is they write a story and then they dole
that thing out 140 characters at a time. So

00:11:54.149 --> 00:12:00.939
it's really just a terrible way to read a
story. Like one sentence every now and t hen

00:12:00.939 --> 00:12:07.429
and you can't really keep up with it. With
the story that I wrote, it was in real time,

00:12:07.429 --> 00:12:12.499
so anything that happened was happening the
same way.

00:12:12.499 --> 00:12:16.611
He ate lunch when you were eating lunch. He
was having coffee in the morning when you

00:12:16.611 --> 00:12:17.791
were having coffee in the morning.

00:12:17.791 --> 00:12:18.791
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: He like coffee a lot.

00:12:18.791 --> 00:12:25.379
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: He loved coffee. I love coffee.
That stuff was honest. Pure, honest love of

00:12:25.379 --> 00:12:31.410
coffee. But when it rained, he complained
about the rain. So there's a lot of real interplay

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:35.940
there. But the other thing was, and this happened
early on.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:43.829
So like I said, the entertainment value for
me at the very beginning was how do I these

00:12:43.829 --> 00:12:50.889
really weird profane word combinations. But
that's not a lot of sustainability in terms

00:12:50.889 --> 00:12:59.819
of mental enjoyment, thankfully I guess right
, for my own psyche. And so then it became,

00:12:59.819 --> 00:13:04.660
'cause a lot of it, especially early on, was
written as I rode the train.

00:13:04.660 --> 00:13:09.059
I live in Evanston. I work downtown. So I
take the Metro in and then walk from the Metro

00:13:09.059 --> 00:13:16.019
to my office. So the total time between those
two things is about an hour. So a lot of the

00:13:16.019 --> 00:13:22.189
tweeting is going to, or coming from, work.
And I started to entertain myself by writing

00:13:22.189 --> 00:13:26.980
these little story arcs. Something would happen
and then something else.

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:31.239
They probably started out as like, three Tweet
arcs, but it would be a beginning, middle,

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:38.589
and an end little mini story. And that might
unfold over 20 minutes or something. And in

00:13:38.589 --> 00:13:44.189
between each one of those beats, three, five,
let's say five tweets. In between each one

00:13:44.189 --> 00:13:48.589
of those five tweets, you're immediately getting
feedback from the people that are reading

00:13:48.589 --> 00:13:55.980
it, which is a really interesting way to write
a story because it completely influences the

00:13:55.980 --> 00:14:00.850
way the thing that you set out to tell, the
way it progresses.

00:14:00.850 --> 00:14:05.499
It might. What it ended up doing was slowing
down those arcs, a lot of the time because

00:14:05.499 --> 00:14:12.999
you suddenly saw people react to them. Oftentimes,
like seeing things that you didn't see. So

00:14:12.999 --> 00:14:19.209
it was like, "Oh, whoa. That's a totally cool
idea. Let's move in that direction." Or just

00:14:19.209 --> 00:14:28.779
the interplay of reaction and writing was
really complicated and very much influenced

00:14:28.779 --> 00:14:31.169
the entire way the thing progressed.

00:14:31.169 --> 00:14:35.649
'Cause it was these little mini arcs and you
just see how people reacted to those arcs.

00:14:35.649 --> 00:14:41.459
