00:46:43.839 --> 00:46:48.380
that spelled it out and I'm positive whoever
lived at that number got like a trillion phone

00:46:48.380 --> 00:46:51.090
calls, 'cause nobody got the joke.

00:46:51.090 --> 00:46:55.400
[laughter]

00:46:55.400 --> 00:47:02.430
But this guy, Alexis Madrigal from the Atlantic,
he wrote same exact kind of at reply on Election

00:47:02.430 --> 00:47:09.020
Day. In my head, I knew the account was ending.
By that point in my head, there was so much

00:47:09.020 --> 00:47:18.420
attention on the thing that I couldn't keep
the secret once it was over. Because it just

00:47:18.420 --> 00:47:21.910
was, It was difficult to live.

00:47:21.910 --> 00:47:28.260
I mean, it sounds stupid, but it was very,
very hard to feel all of this pressure and

00:47:28.260 --> 00:47:35.359
all of these people hunting for you and to
exist in the world. You had to kind of remove

00:47:35.359 --> 00:47:40.000
yourself from the world. I mean, my own personal
Twitter account, I'd barely tweeted at all

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.151
in the last couple weeks 'cause it was just
like I can't engage in the world.

00:47:43.151 --> 00:47:48.371
And I needed to be able to engage in the world.
So I knew I needed it to end. I knew the story

00:47:48.371 --> 00:47:53.869
was ending. And this guy writes an at reply.
And I write him back and just told him to

00:47:53.869 --> 00:48:01.430
fuck himself the same way everyone else gets
it. And he wrote back and tried again and

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:05.500
I think I ignored him. Then he wrote again
to be like, "Well at least you owe me another

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:06.630
'fuck off'."

00:48:06.630 --> 00:48:13.630
And so I think I told him that. And then he
wrote one more time and wa,. Or, I think my

00:48:13.630 --> 00:48:19.289
second reply was like, "Look, I've got an
election to win and a time vortex to disintegrate

00:48:19.289 --> 00:48:23.711
into. I don't have time for you." Or something
like that. And he wrote back and was like,

00:48:23.711 --> 00:48:29.039
"Everyone has 15 minutes." And included, in
a public at reply, his Gmail account.

00:48:29.039 --> 00:48:30.200
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Yeah.

00:48:30.200 --> 00:48:35.740
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: And so I was like, well that's
funny. Who is this guy anyway? And so I looked

00:48:35.740 --> 00:48:40.410
it up and it turns out he used to write for
Wired and now he's the tech editor and a senior

00:48:40.410 --> 00:48:45.630
writer at the Atlantic online. And I was like,
"That's an interesting, that's a good pedigree."

00:48:45.630 --> 00:48:50.460
And I threw it out to the collection of people
that knew the secret, like, "Who is this guy?

00:48:50.460 --> 00:48:51.980
Do any of you know him?"

00:48:51.980 --> 00:48:55.980
And one of them actually had a friend that
knew him. So it was like, "OK, this is someone

00:48:55.980 --> 00:49:02.010
who is writing about stuff that I like in
a publication that I have a great deal of

00:49:02.010 --> 00:49:08.849
respect for. He's known as being a decent
person among the people that I'm really trusting

00:49:08.849 --> 00:49:15.200
here. I'll give it a shot." So when I had
registered the account, I didn't use my own

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:16.200
email address.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:23.810
I used a Gmail account that I'd set up. Gmail,
good times, untraceable, right. And so, I

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:30.490
was like, "OK. I'm gonna write him from that
account." And so I wrote him an email. The

00:49:30.490 --> 00:49:31.990
subject line just said, "OK, Asshole."

00:49:31.990 --> 00:49:34.210
[laughter]

00:49:34.210 --> 00:49:38.480
And then it just said two things. It said,
"One, you mention this tweet, this blog, about

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:43.609
it, it's over before it even begins. Two,
you're the journalist. Pitch me." And he wrote

00:49:43.609 --> 00:49:48.529
me back with a pitch and it was really not
a very good pitch. And so, I wrote him back.

00:49:48.529 --> 00:49:51.809
And I was like, "No, that sounds boring. I'm
gonna go to the New York Times instead."

00:49:51.809 --> 00:49:56.059
Which was totally like one of the back and
forths was me constantly threatening to go

00:49:56.059 --> 00:50:02.150
to the New York Times. And so, he wrote back
and he's like,. It basically was like, "Well,

00:50:02.150 --> 00:50:08.940
if that sounds boring, what sounds good?"
And I wrote back and was like, "I'm not doing

00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:15.940
your job for you, basically." And then, I
think it was that one, where I finally was

00:50:15.940 --> 00:50:18.559
like, "The New York Times."

00:50:18.559 --> 00:50:23.150
I don't know. We had a few more. Then there
was finally one where I wrote back and I said,

00:50:23.150 --> 00:50:26.411
"You know, I don't know. What you're promising
isn't very interesting. The New York Times

00:50:26.411 --> 00:50:30.299
says they'll give me all the piggy back rides
I want and a pony." [Bian Fitzpatrick laughs]

00:50:30.299 --> 00:50:35.369
And he wrote back and he said, "Oh, great.
Now I'm gonna have to kill everyone at the

00:50:35.369 --> 00:50:37.160
New York Times and every pony."

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:39.630
[laughter]

00:50:39.630 --> 00:50:43.400
That's a pretty good response. I mean, so
then it was like, "Huh."

00:50:43.400 --> 00:50:44.400
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I'll play ball.

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:50.039
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. So then, I mean literally,
it was dating. I think he counted it. There

00:50:50.039 --> 00:50:56.740
were 60 emails exchanged between us and a
lot of them were just jokes, like me being

00:50:56.740 --> 00:50:57.740
rude to him.

00:50:57.740 --> 00:50:59.070
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: How long was that? A
couple days, or a week?

00:50:59.070 --> 00:51:00.070
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: No, it

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:01.070
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: It wasn't even a week.
It was.

00:51:01.070 --> 00:51:08.030
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Forty-eight hours, maybe. But
it was just testing. I think I was testing

00:51:08.030 --> 00:51:17.609
him to see who he was, how he thinks, how
he could respond to stuff. And he was testing

00:51:17.609 --> 00:51:24.829
me to just see is there really anything here.
But we bounced back and forth.

00:51:24.829 --> 00:51:32.799
And I think it was the end. Let me think.
The election was on a Tuesday. The account

00:51:32.799 --> 00:51:38.450
ended on a Wednesday. So it was on that Thursday
that I finally wrote to him and was like,

00:51:38.450 --> 00:51:43.950
"I'm gonna drop pretense." So, we communicated
for two days with me basically writing to

00:51:43.950 --> 00:51:46.250
him in character.

00:51:46.250 --> 00:51:51.210
And finally on that Thursday I think I wrote
him and I was like, "I'm gonna drop all pretense

00:51:51.210 --> 00:51:57.450
here. Here is my misgivings." And I think
what I said was, "I'm very nervous that my

00:51:57.450 --> 00:52:05.079
life might get a little crazy when this comes
out. And as a result, I'm very ambivalent

00:52:05.079 --> 00:52:09.490
about it coming out. And I want it to come
out the right way, if it does."

00:52:09.490 --> 00:52:14.029
And he wrote me back this super long email
that started out like, "I totally get it.

00:52:14.029 --> 00:52:18.761
I've had some friends that I think," he wrote,
"descended into the media vortex and it was

00:52:18.761 --> 00:52:25.500
hard to see that happen to them." But then
he also basically was like, "Here's why I

00:52:25.500 --> 00:52:33.109
think the account is really interesting."
And he ends up quoting Russian literature.

00:52:33.109 --> 00:52:39.170
And so, I wrote him. And that was, that's
kind of awesome. I mean, a total ego play

00:52:39.170 --> 00:52:44.960
for him to do that. But a smart one. And so
I wrote him back and I was like, "OK, you'll

00:52:44.960 --> 00:52:48.599
do." That's all the email said. And then my
favorite thing is I didn't write him back

00:52:48.599 --> 00:52:50.210
for hours right after that.

00:52:50.210 --> 00:52:51.210
[Brian Fitzpatrick laughs]

00:52:51.210 --> 00:52:56.849
Like, he wrote right back and then I just
let him stew for a really long time. But then

00:52:56.849 --> 00:53:03.630
we started conversing more directly. And he
did a couple of things that I think were really

00:53:03.630 --> 00:53:10.390
smart. One, he never asked me who I was through
all of this. We were continuing to email just

00:53:10.390 --> 00:53:14.380
through this anonymous account.

00:53:14.380 --> 00:53:21.991
And finally, I was riding in that Friday and
I had already told him like, "Nothing's going

00:53:21.991 --> 00:53:28.799
live this week." I had actually. My wife and
kid and I had already made plans to leave

00:53:28.799 --> 00:53:36.779
town. In part because we really needed a vacation,
but also in part because in my head it was

00:53:36.779 --> 00:53:38.130
like, "I need to get out of here."

00:53:38.130 --> 00:53:43.619
So we were going up to Milwaukee and I was
like, "I wanna have a normal weekend with

00:53:43.619 --> 00:53:48.640
my wife and kid, so nothing's coming out until
Monday. I'm not gonna talk to you until Monday."

00:53:48.640 --> 00:54:01.140
But, on the train in, I realized two things.
One, I'm not just some dude. I've worked very

00:54:01.140 --> 00:54:09.660
hard on a lot of different things for a long
time right ,almost 20 years.

00:54:09.660 --> 00:54:16.460
And all of that stuff adds layers to, I think,
the understanding of the story. So it's not

00:54:16.460 --> 00:54:23.109
fair for him to not know who I am until we
talk on the phone for the first time. So I

00:54:23.109 --> 00:54:27.789
realized that. And I also realized like, "Wait,
how does this guy not know I'm some guy just

00:54:27.789 --> 00:54:33.920
screwing with him?" Like, he put his email
out on a public at reply and he's corresponding

00:54:33.920 --> 00:54:35.369
with an anonymous email account.

00:54:35.369 --> 00:54:40.680
So I wrote him back that morning when I got
into work and I basically was like, "OK, first

00:54:40.680 --> 00:54:46.780
of all, how do know that I'm me? And second
of all, why haven't you asked me who I am?"

00:54:46.780 --> 00:54:53.010
And he wrote back and he said, "I think I
wondered about whether you were you, but there's

00:54:53.010 --> 00:54:57.619
just so much tonally in your writing that
I'm pretty sure it's the same."

00:54:57.619 --> 00:55:06.289
And not profanity, but the other stuff. But
he didn't ask me who I was, which is brilliant.

00:55:06.289 --> 00:55:14.490
'Cause he had totally figured out like, I
needed him to ask me. And he wasn't gonna

00:55:14.490 --> 00:55:21.059
do it. Like, it was so clear he was not gonna
do it. He was gonna make me do it. So, I finally

00:55:21.059 --> 00:55:25.029
wrote him and was like, "OK. This is gonna
happen.

00:55:25.029 --> 00:55:29.019
It's happening on Monday. We're talking on
Monday, but I'm gonna give you the weekend

00:55:29.019 --> 00:55:33.869
to do some research on who I am." And so,
I said, "I'm Dan Sinker." And I hit send.

00:55:33.869 --> 00:55:40.079
And then I was like, "I gotta go teach a class."
So literally in the back of my head in class

00:55:40.079 --> 00:55:43.890
is like, "I'm gonna come outside and there
are gonna be reporters all over."

00:55:43.890 --> 00:55:47.470
Like, what is gonna happen 'cause he's not
gonna hold up his side of the bargain. And

00:55:47.470 --> 00:55:53.210
meanwhile, I'm trying to teach, ironically,
about social media that day.

00:55:53.210 --> 00:55:54.210
[laughter]

00:55:54.210 --> 00:56:00.690
And I came out at break. We had a very early
break that day and he had not revealed it,

00:56:00.690 --> 00:56:06.660
but he had started to research. And I came
in and there was an email at my actual email

00:56:06.660 --> 00:56:12.119
account from him that just said, "Punk Fucking
Planet," with six exclamation points, which

00:56:12.119 --> 00:56:15.140
was this magazine that I'd run for 13 years.

00:56:15.140 --> 00:56:21.599
And it turns out he had come up in the Portland
independent publishing and punk scene. So

00:56:21.599 --> 00:56:26.579
he knew that history. So that was really the
moment where it was like, clearly this was

00:56:26.579 --> 00:56:33.170
all meant to be. And yeah. And then he wrote
the story. It went live on Monday and then.

00:56:33.170 --> 00:56:35.230
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Everything went upside
down.

00:56:35.230 --> 00:56:40.819
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. I mean, my idea of things
might be crazy for a bit and what actually

00:56:40.819 --> 00:56:42.670
happened are.

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:43.940
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Diverse?

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:46.099
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. I'm over here and.

00:56:46.099 --> 00:56:49.310
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Did you expect reporters
on your lawn?

00:56:49.310 --> 00:56:55.240
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: No. The story went live at 1:15.
By three o'clock, local media was on our lawn.

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:56.240
[laughter]

00:56:56.240 --> 00:57:01.051
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I believe the quote from
you was that "there's a fucking reporter on

00:57:01.051 --> 00:57:02.051
my lawn."

00:57:02.051 --> 00:57:06.829
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah, I tweeted that out and
then I did what I think anyone would do in

00:57:06.829 --> 00:57:13.460
that situation, which was dive off of my couch
and crawl across the floor into the bedroom.

00:57:13.460 --> 00:57:14.460
[laughter]

00:57:14.460 --> 00:57:18.690
And then freak out. My wife had come home
early because it became pretty apparent pretty

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:24.760
quickly that this, the reaction to this was
significantly more than we had thought it

00:57:24.760 --> 00:57:31.250
was gonna be. So she came home early, which
was a blessing. But her basic approach was

00:57:31.250 --> 00:57:33.430
like, "If we don't make any sound, they'll
go away."

00:57:33.430 --> 00:57:35.650
[laughter]

00:57:35.650 --> 00:57:39.930
And I was like, "I was sitting in the window.
He walked right; I'm pretty sure he knows

00:57:39.930 --> 00:57:47.850
we're here." And they're ringing the bell
and knocking on windows. And so finally, I

00:57:47.850 --> 00:57:54.619
was like, "I gotta go answer the door." So
I answer the door. My wife furiously is cleaning

00:57:54.619 --> 00:58:02.910
as much of the house as can happen at that
time. And I say to him. It's one guy from

00:58:02.910 --> 00:58:09.680
ABC 7 . I say to him, "Did you have to come
to my house?" 'Cause that felt.

00:58:09.680 --> 00:58:10.789
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Like a violation.

00:58:10.789 --> 00:58:14.960
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Like a violation. I mean, it's
like you're in my house. My kid is coming

00:58:14.960 --> 00:58:22.940
home from school in a half an hour. My neighbors
think I'm an axe murderer now. And he goes,

00:58:22.940 --> 00:58:27.880
"Well, we tried going to your work first,
but you weren't there." I was like, "Oh, great.

00:58:27.880 --> 00:58:29.690
Perfect."

00:58:29.690 --> 00:58:31.500
[laughter]

00:58:31.500 --> 00:58:35.980
And then he says, "Well, just so you know,
like, we're here now. Everyone else will be

00:58:35.980 --> 00:58:41.339
here soon." Meaning, all the other channels.
And he was like, "So you need to think about

00:58:41.339 --> 00:58:44.670
how you wanna do this." I was like, "What
do you mean?" He was like, "Well, there are

00:58:44.670 --> 00:58:45.829
basically two ways you can do this."

00:58:45.829 --> 00:58:46.890
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: The easy way or the hard
way?

00:58:46.890 --> 00:58:47.940
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. That's what I said.

00:58:47.940 --> 00:58:48.940
[Brian Fitzpatrick laughs]

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:54.771
And he chuckled and he said, "Well, no. But
either you can invite us in, each one of us.

00:58:54.771 --> 00:58:58.519
We'll take ten minutes out of your time. We'll
get out of your hair pretty quickly. The story

00:58:58.519 --> 00:59:02.089
will be on the news. It'll be a good story."

00:59:02.089 --> 00:59:07.540
To his credit, he was actually a legitimate
fan of the account. And so, I was very lucky

00:59:07.540 --> 00:59:12.609
that he showed up first, I think. And I was
like, "OK, what's the other way?" 'Cause that

00:59:12.609 --> 00:59:18.299
way did not sound very appealing to me. He
was like, "The other way is you can close

00:59:18.299 --> 00:59:22.829
the door and say, 'I don't wanna talk to you
guys,' and we'll talk to your neighbors and

00:59:22.829 --> 00:59:24.750
we'll go over to your parent's house in Glenview."

00:59:24.750 --> 00:59:30.089
They already knew. They had looked that up.
And he's like, "And we'll do the story that

00:59:30.089 --> 00:59:39.650
way." And I'm like, "That's a kind of a bum
deal." Those are my two choices? So I was

00:59:39.650 --> 00:59:46.180
like, "All right. I'll invite you in." And
so, they came in and shot a thing. And then

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:51.770
everyone else showed up and it was just this
insane local media parade.

00:59:51.770 --> 00:59:57.440
And meanwhile, my email is just like [makes
buzzing noise]. Just emails and my phone is

00:59:57.440 --> 01:00:09.420
going crazy. And yeah. I mean, it was nothing
like I had thought it possibly could have

01:00:09.420 --> 01:00:14.890
been. I mean, it was insane. That 24-hour
period was insane.

01:00:14.890 --> 01:00:20.160
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Well, so let me get this
straight here. So, you had reporters drive

01:00:20.160 --> 01:00:21.980
up from the City of Chicago to Evanston.

01:00:21.980 --> 01:00:22.980
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes.

01:00:22.980 --> 01:00:24.309
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: They're on your front
lawn.

01:00:24.309 --> 01:00:25.309
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes.

01:00:25.309 --> 01:00:28.529
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: And I believe,we're not
gonna name names, here,but several people,

01:00:28.529 --> 01:00:32.780
I believe, asked you, if I recall correctly,
who you voted for in the election.

01:00:32.780 --> 01:00:33.920
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah. I got asked that twice.

01:00:33.920 --> 01:00:35.391
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: For the City of Chicago.

01:00:35.391 --> 01:00:36.391
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

01:00:36.391 --> 01:00:37.619
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: While they're standing
in Evanston at your house.

01:00:37.619 --> 01:00:39.049
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes. In my house.

01:00:39.049 --> 01:00:40.049
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: In your house.

01:00:40.049 --> 01:00:41.701
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: They asked me, "Who did you
vote for?"

01:00:41.701 --> 01:00:43.839
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Well, it is Chicago,
I suppose.

01:00:43.839 --> 01:00:44.839
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Well, you know.

01:00:44.839 --> 01:00:45.902
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: How many times did you
vote for that?

01:00:45.902 --> 01:00:49.760
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: You think it'd be a question
you might've worked out as they crossed the

01:00:49.760 --> 01:00:59.869
border out of Chicago. But they didn't. They
asked it. And my response was basically, "What?"

01:00:59.869 --> 01:01:01.380
But yeah. So, I mean that just.

01:01:01.380 --> 01:01:08.150
The local media.. Then I was on the cover
of the Tribune. Like, the whol,-. Not little

01:01:08.150 --> 01:01:13.171
like that. The story, if it was on the cover,
should've been a little tiny box on the cover,

01:01:13.171 --> 01:01:20.609
but no. It was the whole cover, which interesting
anecdote. I got recognized from the news constantly

01:01:20.609 --> 01:01:23.589
the next few days. And the Tribune?

01:01:23.589 --> 01:01:27.559
Only people consistently citing, "You're the
guy from the newspaper," drunk homeless people.

01:01:27.559 --> 01:01:28.559
[laughter]

01:01:28.559 --> 01:01:29.559
Exclusively.

01:01:29.559 --> 01:01:32.809
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Well now, interestingly
enough, on your personal Twitter account,

01:01:32.809 --> 01:01:35.901
you're often haranguing the Tribune for leading
stories.

01:01:35.901 --> 01:01:36.901
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes.

01:01:36.901 --> 01:01:38.990
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Like there's some huge
thing going on in Wisconsin and they're talking

01:01:38.990 --> 01:01:39.990
about

01:01:39.990 --> 01:01:42.200
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Kraft Beers was their leading
story this week.

01:01:42.200 --> 01:01:44.060
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Yeah, exactly. That's
their lead story. And you continue to do that,

01:01:44.060 --> 01:01:45.430
even though you've already been on the front
page.

01:01:45.430 --> 01:01:46.430
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah.

01:01:46.430 --> 01:01:47.430
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: You're not giving it
up.

01:01:47.430 --> 01:01:51.710
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I mean, no. I mean, the thing
to me is, I teach journalism. And I think

01:01:51.710 --> 01:01:57.609
about media and the impact of media a lot.
To then suddenly be at the center of every

01:01:57.609 --> 01:02:03.910
single thing that I criticize, right. I mean,
it lead the news that night. It was the lead

01:02:03.910 --> 01:02:10.039
story on the news. Second story? Mayor elect
meets with the actual mayor.

01:02:10.039 --> 01:02:19.539
That's the second story because I needed five
minutes at the start, right. That's a poor

01:02:19.539 --> 01:02:26.079
editorial priority. I mean, that's just, that
embodies everything that's wrong with the

01:02:26.079 --> 01:02:32.730
news media right now. And then it's me. I
was like, "Oh, great."

01:02:32.730 --> 01:02:36.140
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So you met. A few days
later you met Rahm.

01:02:36.140 --> 01:02:42.900
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yeah, that was the height of
the media insanity was. Two weeks previous,

01:02:42.900 --> 01:02:47.119
I guess, maybe three weeks previous at that
point, Rahm Emanuel had gone on the radio,

01:02:47.119 --> 01:02:48.769
commercial radio station, which I.

01:02:48.769 --> 01:02:54.550
I mean, I listen to public radio. Like, I'm
that guy. Commercial radio? I hadn't heard

01:02:54.550 --> 01:03:02.990
a commercial radio station since I stopped
calling Z 95 when I was in middle school.

01:03:02.990 --> 01:03:10.250
He goes on WLS radio, on the Roe Conn, Richard
Roeper Show, which is a major drive-time radio

01:03:10.250 --> 01:03:11.250
show.

01:03:11.250 --> 01:03:17.070
And he had said this thing. So I get an email
from, I think it was Roe Conn, or with one

01:03:17.070 --> 01:03:22.690
of their producers that Tuesday, being like,
"OK, Rahm wants you to come on the video.

01:03:22.690 --> 01:03:31.049
He wants to donate money to your charity."
Causes.com, which is a Sean Parker investment

01:03:31.049 --> 01:03:37.789
thing that raises money on Facebook, has agreed
to match this donation.

01:03:37.789 --> 01:03:41.310
Which, the first time he goes on the radio,
he actually says, "I'm gonna donate $2500

01:03:41.310 --> 01:03:47.799
to this person's choice." And then for some
reason, they continue to talk to him and then

01:03:47.799 --> 01:03:55.650
he says $2500 or five thousand. And so then,
as the media echo chamber goes, that canonical

01:03:55.650 --> 01:03:57.619
number was 5,000.

01:03:57.619 --> 01:04:05.250
So, he's in for five grand. They say causes.com
is gonna match it. And so, ten thousand dollars.

01:04:05.250 --> 01:04:11.609
"We need you to be on the radio." Like, I
can't turn ten thousand dollars for a charity

01:04:11.609 --> 01:04:17.769
down. So, I'll go and be on the radio. So
I agree. And so in my head, I'm like, "I'm

01:04:17.769 --> 01:04:22.609
going to be on the radio. No one can see the
radio. We're good, right?

01:04:22.609 --> 01:04:25.319
[chuckles]

01:04:25.319 --> 01:04:29.631
Later that Wednesday. So we're gonna meet
up Wednesday at five at the radio station

01:04:29.631 --> 01:04:37.289
which is downtown. That afternoon, just after
lunch time, they email me the press release

01:04:37.289 --> 01:04:43.700
that they had issued. I'm like, "Oh, I'm not
just gonna be on the radio, am I?" And then

01:04:43.700 --> 01:04:50.609
I get a call from NBC, who had a deal to live
broadcast it live.

01:04:50.609 --> 01:04:54.100
They were the only ones allowed to broadcast
it live. And then they're like, "We need to

01:04:54.100 --> 01:05:00.410
get footage of you walking in the building.
So when will you be arriving?" I'm like, "Oh

01:05:00.410 --> 01:05:05.880
my God. What is this?" And so actually, my
friend Dan O'Neill, I was like, "Please can

01:05:05.880 --> 01:05:10.580
you come help me here?" Se we're walking along
State Street and it's totally that moment

01:05:10.580 --> 01:05:12.329
where I hear someone go like, "There he is."

01:05:12.329 --> 01:05:17.800
And then there's a camera comes running up
and they shoot me going in. And then we get

01:05:17.800 --> 01:05:21.200
in the elevator and then a reporter jumps
in the elevator with me and it's actually

01:05:21.200 --> 01:05:30.730
the same guy who showed up at my house first
thing. And we're going up and I say to him,

01:05:30.730 --> 01:05:33.410
"Who's up there?" And he just goes, "Everyone."

01:05:33.410 --> 01:05:34.630
[laughter]

01:05:34.630 --> 01:05:38.779
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Carl the Intern, Quack
the Duck.

01:05:38.779 --> 01:05:43.980
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: No, he meant everyone from the
media. So they bring me into a room with no

01:05:43.980 --> 01:05:51.520
door, which is really nice. And the media
is swarming outside the doorless room. It

01:05:51.520 --> 01:05:58.430
was like sharks. And you've got the meat in
your shark cage and one of them swims in and

01:05:58.430 --> 01:06:04.980
swims off. And then another one gets a little
bite and then whoomp! I was totally that.

01:06:04.980 --> 01:06:08.599
One would come in and be like, "Hey, how's
it going?" "I'm kinda nervous." And then they'll

01:06:08.599 --> 01:06:11.950
be like, "OK, I'll leave you alone." And they
walk off and then another one would be like,

01:06:11.950 --> 01:06:19.450
"So, my name." And finally, it was like, "Can
we get?" And they're keeping us separate,

01:06:19.450 --> 01:06:22.200
too. They're keeping me and Rahm separate.

01:06:22.200 --> 01:06:31.420
They want the reveal to happen live on the
radio. So they bring me in, finally. They

01:06:31.420 --> 01:06:37.260
allow the shark cage thing to end. And they
bring me into the studio first. And I walk

01:06:37.260 --> 01:06:44.789
into the studio and the studio is, I don't
know, 15 by 20. That makes it sound bigger

01:06:44.789 --> 01:06:49.380
than it was. It was a small room with a big
table in the middle.

01:06:49.380 --> 01:06:53.660
And the two hosts on that side of the table
and two open mics on this side of the table.

01:06:53.660 --> 01:06:58.779
And behind the hosts, was a sea of cameras.

01:06:58.779 --> 01:06:59.779
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Like a firing squad.

01:06:59.779 --> 01:07:07.180
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes, and lights. And I walk
in and my basic reaction is, "Ahhhh."

01:07:07.180 --> 01:07:08.450
[laughter]

01:07:08.450 --> 01:07:16.119
And they make a couple of jokes about that
and then I was just like, "Huh?" And then

01:07:16.119 --> 01:07:19.009
they're like, "OK, we're gonna bring Rahm
in." And so Rahm comes in and he's just like,

01:07:19.009 --> 01:07:21.980
"Hey, how's it going? What's up? Nice to meet
you. OK. Blah, blah, blah."

01:07:21.980 --> 01:07:27.020
And I'm still like, "Huh?" And then they're
talking to him and asking him questions and

01:07:27.020 --> 01:07:30.700
he's just like, "OK, yeah. And blah, blah,
blah, blah, blah. I've totally been prepped

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:34.569
on this and I can talk as much as I want about
whatever it is that I want." And I'm just

01:07:34.569 --> 01:07:39.441
standing in the corner like, "Huh?" And then
they're like, "OK, well thank"

01:07:39.441 --> 01:07:43.839
And he hands me a check and I'm like, "Huh."
And then they're like, "OK, thanks a lot."

01:07:43.839 --> 01:07:48.700
And then he walks out and I'm just standing
there like, "What the fuck just happened?"

01:07:48.700 --> 01:07:49.700
[laughter]

01:07:49.700 --> 01:07:57.740
So people say like, "Oh, you met Rahm." But
I didn't meet Rahm. I was involved in this

01:07:57.740 --> 01:08:06.880
completely surreal, bizarre media event. And
then they sent me back into the windowless

01:08:06.880 --> 01:08:13.069
room while Rahm had a press conference in
the middle of their office. So yeah, that

01:08:13.069 --> 01:08:19.050
was crazy. Thankfully, two things about that
that were actually awesome.

01:08:19.050 --> 01:08:24.450
One, it seemed to rip the Band-Aid completely
off in terms of local news. Like, they got

01:08:24.450 --> 01:08:30.730
to have their shark attack moment and they
were into it. And that quieted down significantly.

01:08:30.730 --> 01:08:37.160
The other thing was, I mean, I have to give
the guy an incredible amount of credit. Like,

01:08:37.160 --> 01:08:39.840
that first of all, they didn't shut the account
down immediately.

01:08:39.840 --> 01:08:47.050
I still don't why they didn't do that. They
could have. Two, they did this bizarre mental

01:08:47.050 --> 01:08:52.390
arithmetic. Like, at some point, there had
to be a discussion. It was like, "OK, do we

01:08:52.390 --> 01:08:55.270
think this guy's a psycho? No. All right.

01:08:55.270 --> 01:09:01.500
Do we think maybe he has a brain? Yes. Do
we think that it wouldn't be the dumbest thing

01:09:01.500 --> 01:09:07.180
in the world to actually acknowledge that
it exists? Yes. Do we think that we should

01:09:07.180 --> 01:09:13.040
actually align ourselves with this thing and
offer to donate a large amount of money to

01:09:13.040 --> 01:09:21.470
any charity that this person picks? Check."
Like, huh? So they did that math.

01:09:21.470 --> 01:09:26.870
I wouldn't have done that math. And they decide
that they are gonna go this charity route.

01:09:26.870 --> 01:09:32.070
Which meant that,. And then causes.com is
like, "Hey, free publicity and the ability

01:09:32.070 --> 01:09:40.120
to donate more." There's a big chunk of change
on the table. And I got to choose, which was

01:09:40.120 --> 01:09:41.120
amazing.

01:09:41.120 --> 01:09:42.120
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: And you chose?

01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:44.700
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I chose an organization called
Young Chicago Authors, which they're best

01:09:44.700 --> 01:09:49.950
known for the Louder than a Bomb poetry, Youth
Poetry Slam contest here in.

01:09:49.950 --> 01:09:52.470
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Did you always have them
in mind from the second the bounty came out?

01:09:52.470 --> 01:09:56.630
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: The moment I heard it, after
I got over the like, "That's never gonna happen,"

01:09:56.630 --> 01:10:01.640
they were the people that I thought immediately
of. I've known about the organization for

01:10:01.640 --> 01:10:07.400
a very long time. They actually profiled me,
I don't know, 15 years ago or something for

01:10:07.400 --> 01:10:09.250
a magazine that they publish called 'Say What.'

01:10:09.250 --> 01:10:13.980
I've had friends that have helped and volunteered
there. They're just a really amazing group

01:10:13.980 --> 01:10:20.250
of people. And the thing that--. And it was
amazing to be able to actually give them a

01:10:20.250 --> 01:10:26.660
sizable amount of money. And the other thing
that was amazing was on Thursday. I still

01:10:26.660 --> 01:10:33.830
was getting local calls and every single call
was, "Why did you choose Young Chicago Authors?"

01:10:33.830 --> 01:10:38.040
All the stories were about Young Chicago Authors
and it was like, "Man. That guy knows how

01:10:38.040 --> 01:10:44.640
to play a chess game." I mean, he knew this
outcome way before anyone else did and it

01:10:44.640 --> 01:10:50.560
was this outcome that actually everyone got
to win from, which is amazing if you think

01:10:50.560 --> 01:10:55.970
about it. But yeah. But that totally ripped
the Band-Aid off the local media. Also, giant

01:10:55.970 --> 01:10:58.240
sex scandal at Northwestern helped, too right.

01:10:58.240 --> 01:11:02.400
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: I believe you thanked
that guy a little bit later.

01:11:02.400 --> 01:11:08.660
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: I did. I actually got an email
from a professor at Northwestern, an English

01:11:08.660 --> 01:11:14.240
professor, who's now teaching the at MayorEmanuel
stuff in his Chicago literature class. He

01:11:14.240 --> 01:11:18.120
wrote me that day and I wrote him back and
I was like, "Please express my thanks to your

01:11:18.120 --> 01:11:21.600
colleague for removing the media circus."

01:11:21.600 --> 01:11:28.390
And then we moved into more of a national
media focus, which was MSNBC, and then insanely,

01:11:28.390 --> 01:11:29.390
The Colbert Report.

01:11:29.390 --> 01:11:30.600
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: How was that?

01:11:30.600 --> 01:11:33.910
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: It was awesome. It was so cool.
I mean,.

01:11:33.910 --> 01:11:35.980
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: He seemed completely
disarmed by you.

01:11:35.980 --> 01:11:40.811
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: He was. I got high-fives from
stage hands afterwards. They were like, "I've

01:11:40.811 --> 01:11:45.890
never seen him do that." It was great. They
called. I was actually being interviewed by

01:11:45.890 --> 01:11:50.080
the student reporter for the Columbia Chronicle
at my office, and they called.

01:11:50.080 --> 01:11:55.471
And her side of the conversation must have
been hilarious to hear 'cause it was just

01:11:55.471 --> 01:12:02.920
me being like, "No it isn't. No. Who is this,
really?" Like, "You're not The Colbert Report."

01:12:02.920 --> 01:12:07.070
But they did. They called and they said, "We
like to bring you out to New York on Tuesday

01:12:07.070 --> 01:12:18.120
and we'd like to have you on." And I follow
Colbert and Jon Stewart through,.

01:12:18.120 --> 01:12:22.560
I don't have cable. So I don't watch it every
day, but I'm certainly very familiar with

01:12:22.560 --> 01:12:29.330
the show and I think what both of them do
is pretty amazing. But I will fully admit

01:12:29.330 --> 01:12:33.460
to be one of those people that watches the
start and the interview comes on and I may

01:12:33.460 --> 01:12:37.120
watch it, and I may not watch it. So, I agreed
to do it.

01:12:37.120 --> 01:12:40.460
And then that whole weekend was just people
being like, "How could you have agreed to

01:12:40.460 --> 01:12:47.610
be interviewed by Stephen Colbert? He's gonna
murder you. Watch out." The best thing you

01:12:47.610 --> 01:12:52.040
can possibly do to someone that's going to
be on The Colbert Report is not write them

01:12:52.040 --> 01:12:55.890
an email that says, "You must be so nervous."

01:12:55.890 --> 01:13:04.310
Which I must have gotten 300 of over the course
of a 24-hour period. So I hadn't been nervous.

01:13:04.310 --> 01:13:10.920
I was just really excited and then I got very
nervous. But it turned out it was great. I

01:13:10.920 --> 01:13:18.370
mean, they do some very smart things. One
of which is just to have this really awesome

01:13:18.370 --> 01:13:25.900
person who hangs out with you when you're
backstage and occupies your brain so that

01:13:25.900 --> 01:13:28.440
I never really felt very nervous.

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:35.900
I'm a person that is prone to getting nervous.
And this person, she was great. She had a

01:13:35.900 --> 01:13:39.830
really cute dog, which helped. So I was hanging
out with her dog and chatting with her about

01:13:39.830 --> 01:13:42.930
her dog for. But she's just keeping your brain
moving.

01:13:42.930 --> 01:13:44.240
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So you can't stew.

01:13:44.240 --> 01:13:48.370
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Right. And then finally, she's
like, "Oh, we should go backstage." And it's

01:13:48.370 --> 01:13:52.770
like, "OK. Let's go backstage." And you're
walking backstage, talking about when TV on

01:13:52.770 --> 01:13:55.810
the radio were on and then she's like, "Oh,
we should go sit down."

01:13:55.810 --> 01:14:00.770
And it's like, "OK, cool. Let's go sit down."
And you go and sit down and you're still just

01:14:00.770 --> 01:14:03.960
chatting with her and she's like, "OK, well
I'm gonna go in back." And it's like, "Oh,

01:14:03.960 --> 01:14:06.961
well thanks. It's been great hanging out with
you." And then she turns around and they're

01:14:06.961 --> 01:14:11.460
like, "And action." Like literally, there's
no pause there.

01:14:11.460 --> 01:14:19.000
So the time it took Stephen to run from his
desk, around the crowd and sit down in front

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:27.160
of me, was the sum total time that I had to
be nervous. So it was great. And then he sat

01:14:27.160 --> 01:14:30.550
down and just let me tell this ridiculous
story, which doesn't,

01:14:30.550 --> 01:14:33.950
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: He looked like he was
trying to hold it together. I thought he was

01:14:33.950 --> 01:14:34.950
gonna lose it.

01:14:34.950 --> 01:14:35.950
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: No, seriously.

01:14:35.950 --> 01:14:36.950
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: No?

01:14:36.950 --> 01:14:39.230
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: If you watch the thing, most
of the time they're showing me, right?

01:14:39.230 --> 01:14:40.230
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: Yeah.

01:14:40.230 --> 01:14:46.200
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: But my angle was of this. He
had his head in his hand like just, sparkles

01:14:46.200 --> 01:14:54.490
in his eye and just smiling. And it was like,
this is awesome. So yeah. I mean, it was of

01:14:54.490 --> 01:14:58.100
all of the media that I did and I did a lot.

01:14:58.100 --> 01:15:06.510
And I didn't want to do most of it. It was
amazing. It was so much fun. It was,. The

01:15:06.510 --> 01:15:14.280
feedback that I got from both people that
I really respect and from just seemingly everyone

01:15:14.280 --> 01:15:21.870
was great. And they were just so nice. Every
single person that I met there just clearly

01:15:21.870 --> 01:15:26.890
loved their job, which is just a great thing.
Just to be able to walk in every day and be

01:15:26.890 --> 01:15:30.200
like, "Man, I'm so,." Like the makeup woman.

01:15:30.200 --> 01:15:36.060
She's done it for 30 years and has worked
at Colbert for, I think, from the start. And

01:15:36.060 --> 01:15:40.930
you could just tell she loved it. It was awesome.

01:15:40.930 --> 01:15:45.230
&gt;&gt;Brian Fitzpatrick: So, he ended up with
two questions. One you wanted to smoke your

01:15:45.230 --> 01:15:46.230
beard, I believe.

01:15:46.230 --> 01:15:47.230
&gt;&gt;Dan Sinker: Yes. That didn't happen.

